  {
    "index": 3,
    "hash": "QHjKioRgfYclPeoA4yeprLqw5vs=",
    "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:31.000Z",
    "action": {
      "type": "SET_CONTENT",
      "input": {
        "content": "The fully-decentralized architecture (D) works by treating Swarm as a native channel rather than a special-case plugin:\n\n**Architecture**: `SwarmChannel` implements the `IChannel` interface (inbox / outbox / deadLetter) and plugs into the reactor's existing `SyncManager`. It replaces the `GqlRequestChannel` that normally talks to a Switchboard server.\n\n**Why this works**: the SyncManager is already designed against an abstract channel. It moves `SyncEnvelope` payloads through whatever channel it's given. It does not know or care whether those envelopes end up going over GraphQL HTTP or over Swarm feeds.\n\n**Result**: \"Swarm IS the Switchboard\" \u2014 from the SyncManager's perspective, the remote is still a remote; only the transport changed.\n\n**Practical implications**:\n- No special-case reactor code paths for Swarm\n- Collaboration uses the same sync primitives, just delivered over feeds/PSS\n- The existing operation semantics (ordering, idempotence, keyframes) carry over\n- Migration between architectures is largely a channel-factory swap\n\nThis is the foundation for `CompositeChannelFactory` as well \u2014 both GQL and Swarm channels can be active for dual-sync (Architecture C).",
        "updatedAt": "2026-05-13T13:00:31.000Z"
      },
      "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:31.000Z"
    }
  },
